<DOC><DOCNO> AP880713-0209 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 2133EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-13 0178</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0182</SECOND><HEAD>Government Says 88 Guerrillas Killed</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Kabul radio said Wednesday thatsecurity forces had killed 88 guerrillas in Afghanistan's easternprovinces, but gave no figures on government casualties.   It said 45 ``extremist elements,'' the Communist government'sterm for Moslem insurgents, were killed in Wardak province and 43during two operations in Nangarhar province near the border withPakistan.   The radio did not say when the battles occurred or give thesites in the provinces.   Guerrillas began fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978,and Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979.More than 5 million Afghans have fled the country and at least 3million live in cities and refugee camps just inside Pakistan.   Soviet troops are withdrawing under a U.N.-mediated agreementsigned April 14 by Afghanistan and Pakistan, with the Soviet Unionand United States as guarantors.   The pullout began May 15 and is to be completed by Feb. 15,1989. More than 30,000 of the estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiershave left so far, according to U.N. figures.</TEXT></DOC>